a","marks":1,"options":["It is responsible for generating action potentials","It encircles each myofibril and stores calcium ions","It stores sodium ions for muscle contraction","It forms a dyad with T-tubules in skeletal muscle","It is a type of mitochondrion found in muscle cells"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe sarcoplasmic reticulum \u003Cstrong\u003Eencircles each myofibril and stores calcium ions\u003C/strong\u003E. This structure is crucial for muscle contraction as it releases calcium ions in response to action potentials, allowing for the interaction of actin and myosin filaments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAction potentials \u003C/strong\u003Eare generated by the plasma membrane, not the sarcoplasmic reticulum. The sarcoplasmic reticulum stores calcium ions, not \u003Cstrong\u003Esodium ions. \u003C/strong\u003EIn skeletal muscle, the sarcoplasmic reticulum forms a triad with T-tubules, not a \u003Cstrong\u003Edyad\u003C/strong\u003E. The sarcoplasmic reticulum is a specialised endoplasmic reticulum, not a \u003Cstrong\u003Emitochondrion.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The sarcoplasmic reticulum is a specialised form of endoplasmic reticulum in muscle cells that stores calcium ions.","The sarcoplasmic reticulum encircles each myofibril and plays a crucial role in muscle contraction by releasing calcium ions.","The sarcoplasmic reticulum forms a triad with T-tubules in skeletal muscle, facilitating rapid transmission of action potentials."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 6; pg. 81.","Patton KT, Thibodeau GA. Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2018.","Hutson M, Ward A, editors. Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press; 2015.","Longo UG, Denaro V, editors. Textbook of musculoskeletal disorders. Springer Nature; 2023.","Hughes SH. The Musculoskeletal System: The Musculoskeletal System-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2022.","Frontera WR, Ochala J. Skeletal muscle: a brief review of structure and function. Calcif Tissue Int. 2015 Mar;96(3):183-95.","Morrison BM. Neuromuscular Diseases. Semin Neurol. 2016 Oct;36(5):409-418."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96303"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18393"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96303"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T14:51:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T14:51:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11111"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114303"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"m